article.description: LaToya Thomas scored 35 points to lead No. 14 Mississippi State to a 72-59 win over No. 15 Arkansas on Thursday.
article.headline: Thomas leads Lady Bulldogs with 35 points
article.linkText: Mississippi State leads Fanning to first win at Arkansas
article.story:
FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Sarah Pfeifer's eyes glistened with
tears after Arkansas' 72-59 loss to Mississippi State (No. 12 ESPN/USA Today, No. 14 AP) on Thursday night.

	   "We were prepared; we had two great practices,'' the Arkansas
freshman said. "Nobody knows how to explain it. ... I don't have a
word for it.''

	   Mississippi State coach Sharon Fanning explained it very well,
attributing her players' victory to their play.

	   "They were guarding hard and helping each other,'' Fanning
said. "A lot of things to build a lead -- contesting shots and
trying to limit second shots.''

	   LaToya Thomas scored 35 points to lead Mississippi State (19-6,
7-4 Southeastern Conference), and Tan White had 25 points for the
Lady Bulldogs, combining for 60 points, one more than Arkansas'
total score.

	   Mississippi State won for the first time at Bud Walton Arena in
Fanning's eight years at the helm.

	   "This was no doubt a tremendous win for our program,'' Fanning
said.

	   Shameka Christon scored 14 points for the Lady Razorbacks (19-7,
6-5), while Pfeifer had 12 and India Lewis added 11. It was the
second home loss of the season for Arkansas (No. 14 ESPN/USA Today, No. 15 AP).

	   The teams had to play the final four minutes with two referees
after the third member of the officiating crew, Lisa Pitts,
suffered a head wound after sliding into metal risers at the
baseline. The Arkansas team doctor examined Pitts and she was taken
to a local hospital to get stitches, said Bill Smith, director of
women's sports information.

	   The Lady Bulldogs led 36-19 at halftime and held Arkansas
scoreless for the first 4:45 of the second half. A 3-pointer by
Blessing Chekwa gave Mississippi State a 45-19 lead.

	   Later in the half, Christon hit a 3-pointer. Lewis followed with
a basket to narrow the Lady Bulldogs' lead to 64-53 with three
minutes remaining.

	   Arkansas outscored Mississippi State 40-36 after the break, but
it wasn't enough to make up for a first half in which the Lady
Razorbacks hit just 25 percent of their shots from the field.

	   Arkansas doubled its shooting percentage in the second half,
shooting 56 percent for 39.6 percent overall, compared to
Mississippi State's 41 percent for the game.

	   "I don't care what their shooting percentage was ... because it
seemed like they were shooting 70 percent,'' Arkansas head coach
Gary Blair said. "It seemed like they were shooting so many layups
the whole night. I don't think I've ever had a team shoot that many
layups against the zone (defense) ... than I have in my whole
life.''

	   Mississippi State started the game with a 9-0 run -- including
six points from Thomas -- until Harper hit a 15-footer.

	   White and Doceide Warren hit 3-pointers midway through the half
to increase the Lady Bulldogs' lead to 21-2.

	   Arkansas didn't score again until more than five minutes later
when Christon landed a layup and a free throw.

	   "We just felt like we could weather the storm and fight our way
back in it,'' Blair said. "But when we got it to 14 in the first
half, if we could have just kept fighting ... but it just didn't
work that way. We just kept giving up.''
